1. Check what’s consuming space

Start by identifying which directories under /home are growing:

du -sm /home/* | sort -n

Then drill down into the biggest one:

du -sm /home/<suspect_dir>/* | sort -n

2. Common reasons DB2 uses /home

a) Instance home directory
When you created the DB2 instance user (e.g. db2inst1), its home directory is usually under /home/db2inst1.
DB2 stores a lot there:

instance configuration (sqllib)
diagnostic logs (db2dump)
sometimes database directories (if created with relative paths)

👉 If databases were created without specifying a path, they may default inside the instance home.
b) Diagnostic logs filling up
Check:

/home/db2inst1/sqllib/db2dump

Files like:

db2diag.log
.trc files
.dump files

These can grow very large.

c) Transaction logs
If log path wasn’t explicitly set, logs might be under /home.

Check inside DB:

db2 get db cfg for <dbname> | grep -i log

Look for:

Path to log files

d) Temporary tablespaces / sort space
Large queries can spill temp data if configured poorly.

3. Immediate cleanup (safe checks)

Be careful, but you can usually:

Rotate or truncate diag logs:
> db2diag.log
Remove old dump files:
rm -f *.dump *.trc
4. Long-term fixes

Move logs out of /home:

db2 update db cfg for <dbname> using NEWLOGPATH /db2logs

Move database storage:

Create new tablespaces in another filesystem
Or restore DB to a new location

Change diagnostic path:

db2 update dbm cfg using DIAGPATH /db2diag
5. Best practice layout (AIX + DB2)

Avoid putting DB2-heavy data in /home. Use separate filesystems:

/db2data → tablespaces
/db2logs → transaction logs
/db2backup → backups
/db2diag → diagnostics
6. Quick sanity check

Run:

df -g /home

If it’s near 100%, act quickly—DB2 can stop or crash if it can’t write logs.

