✅ Method 1: Using DB2 command

Run this as the instance user (e.g. db2inst1):

db2 get dbm cfg | grep -i diagpath

You’ll get output like:

Diagnostic data directory path (DIAGPATH) = /home/db2inst1/sqllib/db2dump

👉 That path is where db2diag.log and other diagnostic files are stored.

✅ Method 3: Find the file directly

If you're unsure, search for it:

find / -name db2diag.log 2>/dev/null
⚠️ Important

If your /home is filling up, and you see something like:

/home/db2inst1/sqllib/db2dump/db2diag.log

then that’s likely the culprit.

🔧 If you want to move it

You can change the diag path:

db2 update dbm cfg using DIAGPATH /new/path
db2stop
db2start

Make sure the new directory:

exists
has proper ownership (db2inst1)
has enough space
